definition.value: MIC sign (>, <, =) of the MIC value.
Greater than MIC value.
Less than MIC value.
Equal to MIC value.
MIC is a range of two MIC values (e.g., given 10 clinical isolates with a resistance determinant, there are 5 that have an MIC of 25ug/mL and 5 that have an MIC of 100ug/mL agaisnt tobramycin).
Strain type used for antibiotic susceptibility testing.
Resistant determinant is identified in strain without any experimental methods.
Experimental deletion of resistance determinant in the chromosome of the strain initially with this resistance determinant.

label.value: deletion of resistance determinant with plasmid harbouring resistance determinant

definition.value: Experimental protocol where there is a deletion of resistance determinant and the transformation of a plasmid harbouring resistance determinant into the same strain.
Experimental procedure where plasmid harbouring a resistance determinant is transformed into a strain.
Without any experimental protocol, the resistance determinant is absent from the strain.
Experimental insertion of resistance determinant in the chromosome of the strain initially without this resistance determinant.
Specific strain of bacteria that was used to perform the antibiotic susceptibility test.
Source of the strain used in the antibiotic susceptibility test (e.g., clinical, environmental, agriculture).
Strain isolated in a clinical setting (e.g., from a patient).
Strain collected from environment (e.g., soil, water).
Strain collected from agricultural setting (e.g., chicken, pig).

The control of the antibiotic susceptibility testing, whether there was an experimental control (same strain, with and without resistance determinant) or if there was a group of clinical isolates found to have a resistance determinant compared against a strain without that resistance determinant.
Antimicrobial susceptibility testing was performed on the same strain with and without a resistance determinant.

Antibiotic susceptibility testing is performed on a group of clinical isolates with a resistance determinant compared to different strains that do not have this resistance determinant. No experiment was performed to delete / insert the resistance determinant to determine antibiotic susceptibility using the same genetic background.

value.value: A chromosomal macrolide 2'-phosphotransferase and resistance gene identified from a Brachybacterium faecium cave isolate.

definition.value: Source is an experimental, commonly used lab strain (e.g., P. aeruginosa PAO1).

value.value: A chromosomal macrolide phosphotransferase identified from Bacillus subtilis.
A macrolide phosphotransferase identified on a plasmid in Exiguobacterium.
A chromosomal macrolide phosphostransferase identified in Brachybacterium paraconglomeratum.
A chromosomal macrolide phosphotransferase identified in Brevibacillus brevis VM4.
ADC beta-lactamase enzymes with demonstrable carbapenemase activity, an exception amongst these enzymes.

label.value: Campylobacter jejuni 23S rRNA with mutation conferring resistance to erythromycin

value.value: Point mutations in the 23S ribosomal RNA domain of Campylobacter jejuni which confer resistance to macrolide antibiotics, including erythromycin.
A dihydrofolate reductase and antibiotic resistance gene identified from an integron in Vibrio cholerae.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene identified from porcine isolates of Esherichia coli.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene identified from an integron in Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene from non-O1, non-O139 Vibrio cholerae.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene from Aeromonas hydrophilia.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene from Klebsiella pneumoniae.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene isolated from canine Escherichia coli infection.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene identified from non-typhoidal multidrug-resistant Salmonella enterica.
A dihydrofolate reductase and trimethoprim resistance gene identified on an integron in multidrug-resistant gram-negative bacteria.
CAM (Central Alberta Metallo) beta-lactamases are class B metallo-beta-lactamases and carbapenemases found to confer resistance to broad spectrum antibiotics in Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
CAM-1 is a CAM (Central Alberta Metallo) beta-lactamase and carbapenemase identified from 4 clinical isolates of Pseudomonas aeruginosa from a Canadian hospital.
murG acetylglucosaminyltransferase enzymes inhibited by vancomycin. Mutations in murG confer resistance to vancomycin through antibiotic target alteration.

label.value: Clostridioides difficile murG with mutation conferring resistance to vancomycin

value.value: Mutations in murG which confer resistance to vancomycin in Clostridioides difficile.

label.value: Clostridioides difficile gyrB conferring resistance to fluoroquinolones

value.value: Point mutations in gyrB of Clostridioides difficile conferring resistance to fluoroquinolone antibiotics.

label.value: Clostridioides difficile rpoB with mutation conferring resistance to rifampicin

value.value: Point mutations in the rpoB region of Clostridioides difficile which confer resistance to rifampin and rifampicin antibiotics.
Resistance-modifying agent (RMA) without characterized mechanism which do not exhibit antibiotic activity on their own, but improve the performance of antibiotic drugs.

A class of resistance-modifying agents and beta-lactam potentiators which selectively potentiate beta-lactam antibiotics, specifically Amoxicillin-clavulanic acid, in methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus (MRSA) without their own antimicrobial activity.
Rifalazil is a rifamycin derivative antibiotic, sometimes used for treating Clostridioides difficile infections.
Ramoplanin is a glycolipodepsipeptide antibiotic derived from gram-positive Actinoplanes used to treat infection with Clostridioides difficile.
A trimethoprim-resistant dihydrofolate reductase identified from Vibrio cholerae.

A chromosomally-encoded colistin resistance phosphoethanolamine (PEtN) transferase of Moraxella osloensis. ICR-Mo represents the closest known ortholog to the colistin resistance MCR-1 and MCR-2 PEtN transferases.

PNGM is a family of metallo-beta-lactamases first identified from a deep-sea sediment metagenome and shown to reduce antibiotic susceptibility by hydrolysis of penicillins, carbapenems and extended- and broad-spectrum cephalosporins.
